A syringe extruder for the 3DRAG.
All the parts are designed with openSCAD so it can be easily adapted to your syringe. Our initial purpose was to use syringes up to 100 millilitres. We designed also a coolant jacket (or heating jacket) in which suitable thermosetting fluid can be pumped. We printed it in ABS. Please note that in order to avoid leakages a small amount of acetone was poured first in the internal chamber of the jacket and then quickly removed.
Another hack is to attach 3x100 ohm resistors instead of the temperature sensor. This allows the extruder to run immediately (if not the temperature reading of the thermistor doesn't allow the printer to start).
In the picture it's visible the final assembly with a criostatic unit attached.

The extruder was designed by Giovanni Canti for his thesis work.

This funky pencil holder, or small vase, was designed in Project Shapeshifter by Autodesk. Hexagons repeat along a wavy path, sharing edges while getting stretched, twisted, and distorted. One end is closed to form a thin, solid base. Full scale puts it at 150mm tall, nearing the Replicator 2 max of 155mm; 90mm OD at top; 48mm OD at bottom. Fairly sturdy and lightweight, it stands upright on the flat base or also on the wavy rim. Print two of them the same size and their wavy rims will interlock when facing each other. Being my first full design done in Shapeshifter I wasn't sure what to expect but I am really happy with it. I have designed a few more funky objects and will happily post a couple of the best ones if there is interest.

Shapeshifter has a great export feature that prompts you for units and file type (.stl or .obj). Unfortunately it does not currently have the ability to Open Previous or Import design files. The good news is that just making it is easy:
  • download .stl and import into MakerWare or similar
  • scale it to the size you want (see notes below on scale)
  • print 1, 2, or 2^n if you're combining them
  • optional: combine 2 rim-to-rim (funky football!) or base-to-base (funky supernova?)
  • enjoy!
    • Scale: Scaling works fine; although the one scaled down print I did was with lower quality filament and it came out a tad hairy (stray strands inside some of the hexagons). I believe the filament is more to blame, but I don't know for sure.

simple 3.5" one eye box google design.

similar to my "Gteng monocle" design(http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2108436), this allows the fpv pilot the ability to easily retain his/her LOS ability while with a simple closing of one eye return to full FPV vision.

this simple fact may very well become quiet important in the present and near future as further regulations are imposed on fpv users that require a constant LOS observer with a additional buddy box if the pilot wishes to fly FPV, this is due to the fact that when using current fpv goggles your eyesight is completely obscured making LOS impossible.

I designed this as a work around the regulation, the regs though restrictive are still very vague in the whole LOS position meaning that aslong as you can retain LOS with even just one eye you are still flying legally in terms of the regs (least till some busybody no knowledge beaurocrat gets picky) even without a additional observer present with a buddybox setup.

this makes the impracticality of dragging along a spouse/random friend/some other poor sod to stand about holding a buddybox transmitter while looking bored unnecessary and we fpv'ers can get back to what we do best, flying our frames safely not bothering anyone.

the design uses this dashboard monitor stripped from its casing:-
https://www.banggood.com/TFT-LCD-Screen-Monitor-for-Car-Rear-Rearview-Backup-Camera-p-908698.html?rmmds=myorder
and then slotted into the housing with the control buttons on the housings side, simple right?, then the only additional items needed are a 3x magnification Fresnel lens or two if wear glasses and need to adjust the focal range more precisely (credit card sized....found all over ebay) and a elasticated headstrap (you can buy spare box goggle head straps from ebay too).

then just add a bit of foam tape round the face contact points and presto you have a one eyed box goggle setup which allows you to retain LOS still.

just add your prefered Vrx and battery (it'll run of 2s and 3s) and even a Eachine Dvr like I have and you good to go for hours.

description.text: Logo of MT-09

This is the plastic detailing for the front of an iron man arc reactor.
These can be bought assembled or in kit form from my website
https://sites.google.com/site/msraynsford/ironmanarcreactors

I use copper coloured black plastic, this allows me to have multiple colours on the final design (by cutting through the copper). There are 4 circles in the design, each on represents a stage of cutting and the outline circle is never actually cut.
The first two stages are low power etches, the places where it gets cut twice allow some height differences in the final item.
The third stage is a low power cut to expose the black lines meant to look like transformer coils.
The fourth and final stage cuts holes through the plastic to let the light shine through.

description.text:
This is the ultimate MakerBot Font for OpenSCAD! Now tagging and versioning (!) your OpenSCAD models is as easy as writing label("v1.0"). Give it a try! Just put an ID on every print and never lose track of your rapid prototyping evolution! Features:
  • * variable-width characters (eeeevil OpenSCAD hack!)
  • * using new OpenSCAD string-functions (no more array ["m", "a", "d", "n", "e", "s", "s"])
  • * font metrics
  • * text alignment functions
  • * self-contained in one single file
  • * higher and lower resolution fonts are available
    • This file was created with my tool svgFont2scad, which takes care of all the transcoding, bezier curves, compression etc. I plan to release it later this year (currently in PHP, but I want to port it to Python).
    If you have fonts you would like to have converted: Just drop me a line! The font you find here is called Designer Block by K-Type (http://www.k-type.com/?p=296). It's free for personal use but K-Type require a paid license for commercial use. This thing supercedes previous fonts:
    http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:19484
    http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:6844 Current limitations: Only ~64 characters at once.
    Reason (Caution! Geeky stuff!): Since OpenSCAD does not support stateful variables, I use recursions within functions to store variables on the stack. So when entering too many characters, OpenSCAD will just go up in flames!
    (Maybe someone should inform OpenSCAD's Clifford or Marius about this...)

Put the .scad file somewhere OpenSCAD can find it (e.g. your OpenScad/libraries directory or your project directory). Then just go like:
use <font_DesignerBlock_med.scad>
label("Test");
 You can also specify size, height (thickness), spacing, alignment, e.g.
label("Left", align="L");
label("Right", align="R");
label("Big", size=100);
label("Long", height=100); Have fun!

description.text:
This bracket is the same idea as the one by donnyb99 except for the v2 CR-10s that use the metal bracket on the Y axis. I updated the bracket, end cap, and puller. I did not design the knob, this is the same ones as in his design but I added it here for convenience.

This is version 2 of the bracket for the S4. This version is for those with a 10mm belt on the Y axis.

You will need one M5x30 bolt and M5 nut for the puller, four M4x20 to mount to the frame, and one M4x30 for the pulley. This design is a bit beefier than the original for the CR-10 since this part is connected to the frame differently.

Print this with at least 50% infill since where this connects to the frame the part will be squeeze pretty solidly by the bolts. Since I don't want the part to warp and bend there I printed it full. You can use support for the bracket if you want since there is a challenging bridge in it.

In order to assemble this, you have to remove the existing 3D printed idler and keep the four nuts, you will re-use them. Do not undo the two metal L brackets.

Remove the belt from the pulley on the other end of Y-axis so that you have more slack to work with.

Push the M5 bolt all the way into the puller so that the hex head rests inside the cutout for it and the threads protrude out the back of it. You may have to lightly tap the M5 into it's place using a hammer and a screwdriver.

Use the M4x30 bolt to put the lock the idler wheel and belt in place inside the puller. Then put the bracket's onto the two metal L brackets and secure it with the four M4x20 bolts and nuts that you kept when removing the original part.

Push the M5 nut into the slot made for it in idig3d's knob.

Put the belt back onto the pulley at the Y-axis motor.

Lastly, slip the endcap onto the back of the bracket and screw the knob into the M5 bolt.

description.text: I frankened this together from many ideas to make a part that kills quite a few proverbial birds. It's derived mostly from triffid_hunter's http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:12151. Adds a lift to the Z motor like, ROTORIT's http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:12620. Then I added a 608 bearing to keep the z leadscrew in line and arms to support a wade style extruder.

Print a pair and you're all set. Any combination will work. AA would give one extruder mount in the back and the other in the front. AB would put the extruder mount on the same side. You can also use NoArms for one with no extruder mounts. Drop a 608 bearing into the mount. Should be used with something like http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:16126. When adding lock nuts to the leadscrews, set it up so the motors float a bit above the mounts but still inside the "walls" of the mount. This lets the motors wobble without affecting the zscrews. I built up the sides of my motors with Kapton tape so there would be minimal backlash when the z reverses. The SCAD file is "parametrish" and depends on MCAD
https://github.com/elmom/MCAD/zipball/master enjoy!

description.text:
I got tired of the "basic black" mouthpieces SMOK includes with their tanks and atomizers; my mod has color, so why not the tip, too?

Sure, I could buy a resin one that matches, but why not make one myself? I've got the toys to do it.

These tips will work on the TFV8-Baby, the TFV8, the TFV12, the SkyHook tank, and possibly other SMOK atomizers, except the BabyBeast.

I've noticed that SMOK tips have two different sizes of gaskets on them, so I built two separate STLs, one for each. If you pull the gaskets off your existing tip and you think to yourself, "God, those are thin!", then you have the small gasket version.

These tips are larger than the SMOK stock tips, which I think gives a bit better airflow and more flavor. YMMV.

It should go without saying that you should use a FOOD SAFE filament, such as PETG or PLA to print this. If you're not sure if the filament you'd like to use is food safe, contact the manufacturer to find out. I cannot stress this enough: don't potentially poison yourself by using a filament material that may contain toxins.

Best printed as hot as possible for good layer adhesion.

Comments and constructive criticisms are always welcome.

EDIT: I've changed the Big Gasket version slightly to make it fit a little more snugly in the atomizer. If you've downloaded the original file, please download the new one. I've deleted the old version. Thanks.

EDIT2: added the warning about food safe filament, and added a pic of the printed object on a TFV8 tank.

EDIT3: If you were going to print this, and haven't yet, head on over to https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2406174 and print the one with no gaskets necessary!
